    "long_instructions": "# Do This:\r\n\r\n**Refer to Strategy 1 & 2**\r\n\r\n1. **Discuss:** Take a look at the code and discuss what might go wrong before running it.<br>\r\n2. **Trace the Code:** Walk through the program line by line with your partner, explaining aloud what each line does and what you expect to happen. <br>\r\n3. **Use Print Statements:** Add print statements to check when and where different pieces of code run.\r\n    - **Hint:** Try adding print statements inside the function definition, after the object is created, or after the function is called.\r\n    - **Run and test** to see what your print statements reveal.\r\n4. **Modify & Fix the Bug:** Adjust the code to resolve the issue.\r\n\t- **Hint:** Can you use a method on an object before it’s created?\r\n    \r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: black;\">\r\n<h5><strong>📝 Unit Guide</strong></h5>\r\n\r\nDocument your experience with this debugging strategy:\r\n- What worked? \r\n- What challenges did you face? \r\n- How did this strategy help? \r\n- When might it be most useful in the future?\r\n</div>",
    "start_sources": {
      "files": {
        "0": {
          "id": "0",
          "name": "main.py",
          "language": "py",
          "contents": "from neighborhood import Painter\n\ndef move_and_paint(color):\n    painter.paint(color)\n    painter.move()\n    \nmove_and_paint(\"blue\")\n\npainter = Painter()\n\nmove_and_paint(\"red\")\n",
          "folderId": "0",
          "active": true,
          "open": true
        }
      },
      "folders": {
      }
    },
    "teacher_markdown": "Students should use Strategy 2: Code Tracing / Print Statements with this level. \r\n\r\nStudents will manually walk through their code and add print statements to find issues."
